[[File:Girolamo della volpaia, modello dell'orbe lunare, firenze 1557, appartenuto a vincenzo viviani.JPG|thumb|right|Armillary sphere, 1557]]
'''Girolamo della Volpaia''' (ca. 1530-1614) was an Italian maker of [[clock]]s and [[scientific instruments]] from [[Volpaia]].

Girolamo continued the business of his father [[Camillo della Volpaia]] (1484-1560) and his uncles [[Benvenuto della Volpaia]] (1486-1532) and [[Eufrosino della Volpaia]] (late 15th century - 16th century), who were an important family of craftsmen in Tuscany.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mhs.ox.ac.uk/epact/catalogue.php | website=Epact | title=Armillary Sphere | publisher=Museum of the History of Science, Oxford | accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.volpaia.info/della_volpaia.htm | publisher=Volpaia | title=Volpaia - home of clockmakers | accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>  In 1554, he made an [[armillary sphere]], now preserved in the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] in [[London]].<ref name="smg">{{cite web|title=Italian armillary sphere, 1554|url=http://collection.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects/co56284/italian-armillary-sphere-1554-armillary-sphere|publisher=Science Museum Group|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref> In 1560, he succeeded his father as superintendent of the large clock in the [[Palazzo Vecchio]]. He also asked to be assigned the maintenance of his grandfather [[Lorenzo della Volpaia|Lorenzo]]'s (1446-1512) ''Orologio dei Pianeti'' [Planetary Clock], which he restored himself. In 1564, he designed a clock for the [[Piazza San Marco]] in [[Venice]]. In 1590, he built his last clock, preserved at the [[Museo Galileo]] of [[Florence]] (inv. 2460).
<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalogo.museogalileo.it/biografia/GirolamoVolpaia.html|title=Museo Galileo - object description|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>

