{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} A '''hapaxanth''' is a [[plant]] species whose individuals [[flower]] only once in their lifetimes and die subsequently. Other terms with the same meaning are ''[[Reproduction#Other types of reproductive strategies|semelparous]]'' and ''[[monocarpic]]''. The term was first used by [[Alexander Braun]].
This term is used for plants that only have one flowering event and then die. It is used most often in conjunction with describing some of the [[taxa]] of [[Arecaceae]] (palms) and some species of [[bamboo]], but rarely used otherwise. Many [[annual plant|annuals]] flower over a period of time and can have flowers and seeds on the same plant at the same time, thus they are not hapaxanthic, because flowering does not lead to death. A related term is [[pleonanth]]ic, again used with Arecaceae (palms) and some bamboos for stems that flower more than once. Its antonym is often given as ''[[pollakanth]]'', although ''pleonanth'' is also seen.
