[[File:KnutOlaiBjørlykke.jpg|thumb|Knut Bjørlykke]] '''Knut Olai Knutsen Bjørlykke''' (11 February 1860 &ndash; 26 February 1946) was a Norwegian geologist and [[Sedimentology|sedimentologist]]. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://foreninger.uio.no/ngf/ngt/pdfs/NGT_40_3&4_297-312.pdf|title= K. O. Bjørlykke |publisher = Norsk Geologisk Tidsskrift |author= Gunnar Holmsen|accessdate= January 1, 2017 }}</ref>
He was born in [[Sandøy]] in [[Møre og Romsdal]], Norway. He was the father of [[Harald Bjørlykke]]<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Knut Olai Knutsen Bjørlykke|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Knut_Olai_Knutsen_Bj%C3%B8rlykke|language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> and through him a grandfather of [[Arne Bjørlykke]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Arne Bjørlykke|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Arne_Bj%C3%B8rlykke|language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref>
He took the [[dr.philos.]] degree in 1907, and his best known academic work was ''Det centrale Norges fjeldbygning'' (1905). He worked for the [[Norwegian Geological Survey]] from 1889 to 1905 and the [[Norwegian College of Agriculture]] from 1898 to 1931.<ref name="snl"/> He was awarded his [[PhD.]] in 1907 and appointed professor of geology. <ref name=ssb>{{stort15}}</ref>
In the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1915]] he stood as a candidate for the [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]] in the constituency ''Bærum og Follo'', but lost to [[Christian Fredrik Michelet (politician)|Christian Fredrik Michelet]] with only 864 out of 9,133 votes.<ref name=ssb/>
