This is a list of named [[Impact crater|craters]] on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], the [[Inner planets|innermost planet]] of the [[Solar System]] ''(for other features, see [[list of geological features on Mercury]])''.<ref name="Gazetteer-Mercury-Craterlist" /> Most Mercurian craters [[Planetary nomenclature|are named after]] famous writers, artists and composers. According to the rules by IAU's [[Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature]], all new craters must be named after an artist that was famous for more than fifty years, and dead for more than three years, before the date they are named.<ref name=Ritzel/> Craters larger than 250&nbsp;km in diameter are referred to as "basins" ''(also see {{Section link||Terminology}})''.<ref>[https://astrogeology.usgs.gov/Projects/PlanetaryMapping/DIGGEOL/mercury/h7/h7.pdf H-7 text_all.word<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name="Gazetteer-Categories" />

As of 2017, there are 397 named Mercurian craters,<ref name="Gazetteer-Mercury-Craterlist" /> a small fraction of the total number of named Solar System craters, most of which are [[List of craters on the Moon|lunar]], [[List of craters on Mars|Martian]] and [[List of craters on Venus|Venerian]] craters.<ref name="Gazetteer-Moon-Craterlist" /><ref name="Gazetteer-Mars-Craterlist" /><ref name="Gazetteer-Venus-Craterlist" />{{efn|name=WGPSN-Dropped}}

Other, non-planetary bodies with numerous named craters include [[Callisto (moon)|Callisto]] ([[List of craters on Callisto|141]]), [[Ganymede (moon)|Ganymede]] ([[List of craters on Ganymede|131]]), [[Rhea (moon)|Rhea]] (128), [[4 Vesta|Vesta]] (90), [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] (90), [[Dione (moon)|Dione]] (73), [[Iapetus (moon)|Iapetus]] (58), [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]] (53), [[Tethys (moon)|Tethys]] (50) and [[Europa (moon)|Europa]] ([[List of craters on Europa|41]]). For a full list, ''see [[List of craters in the Solar System]]''.

