'''Marina Evseevna Ratner''' ({{lang-ru|Мари́на Евсе́евна Ра́тнер}}; October 30, 1938 – July 7, 2017<ref>[https://math.berkeley.edu/about/history/in-memoriam In Memoriam]: [[University of California, Berkeley]] website.</ref>) was a professor of mathematics at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] who worked in [[ergodic theory]].<ref>Larry Riddle, Biography of [http://www.agnesscott.edu/lriddle/women/ratner.htm Marina Ratner]</ref> Around 1990, she proved a group of major theorems concerning [[unipotent]] [[flow (mathematics)|flows]] on [[homogeneous space]]s, known as [[Ratner's theorems]].<ref>Dave Witte Morris, [http://people.uleth.ca/~dave.morris/lectures/Ratner/Ratner-v1-1.pdf ''Ratner's Theorems on Unipotent Flows''], {{ISBN|0-226-53984-9}}</ref> Ratner was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 1992,<ref>[https://www.amacad.org/multimedia/pdfs/classlist.pdf Membership list], [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], retrieved 2015-06-13.</ref> awarded the [[Ostrowski Prize]] in 1993 and elected to the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] the same year. In 1994, she was awarded the [[John J. Carty Award for the Advancement of Science|John J. Carty Award]] from the National Academy of Sciences.<ref name=Carty>{{cite web|title=John J. Carty Award for the Advancement of Science |url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_carty |publisher=National Academy of Sciences |accessdate=25 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229180532/http://www.nasonline.org/site/PageServer?pagename=AWARDS_carty |archivedate=29 December 2010 |df= }}</ref>
== Biographical information ==
Born in [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]] to a Jewish family, her father was a plant physiologist and mother, a chemist. Ratner's mother was fired from work in the 1940s for writing to her mother in Israel, then considered an enemy of the Soviet state. Ratner gained an interest in mathematics in her fifth grade. She then studied at the [[Moscow State University]] in 1956 where she was inspired by [[Andrey Kolmogorov|A.N. Kolmogorov]] and his group.{{cn|date=October 2018}} Her graduate studies were under [[Yakov Sinai|Yakov G. Sinai]], also a student of Kolmogorov.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=32902}}</ref> She emigrated from the Soviet Union in 1971 after obtaining a Ph.D. to Israel and taught at the Hebrew University 1971–1975. She began to work with [[Rufus Bowen]] at Berkeley and later emigrated to the United States and became a professor of mathematics at Berkeley.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/12/03/Soviet-refusenik-to-be-released/2923565506000/|title=Soviet refusenik to be released|last=Hartsock|first=John|date=1987-12-03|work=UPI|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> Her work included proofs of conjectures dealing with unipotent flows on quotients of Lie groups made by [[S. G. Dani]] and [[M. S. Raghunathan]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Cook, M.|author2=Gunning, R. C.|title=Mathematicians: An Outer View of the Inner World|place=Princeton| publisher= Princeton University Press|year= 2013}}</ref>
