{{infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = Prodigal Genius: The Life of Nikola Tesla | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[John Joseph O'Neill (journalist)|John Joseph O'Neill]] | cover_artist = | illustrator = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = Ives Washburn | release_date = 1944 | english_release_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Prodigal Genius: The Life of Nikola Tesla''''' ({{ISBN|0914732331}}) is a 1944 book by [[John Joseph O'Neill (journalist)|John Joseph O'Neill]] detailing the life of [[Nikola Tesla]].
==Overview== Written by [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author John J. O'Neill, the life of Nikola Tesla details the life of a pioneer in electrical engineering.<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=3921600|title=Books of the Week – Science Review of the Year |journal=The Science News-Letter |volume=46 |number=26 |date=23 December 1944 |page=416}}</ref> O'Neill was a close friend of Tesla, whom he had met as a boy and remained in contact with.<ref>{{cite book |title=Dr. Nikola Tesla: The Forgotten Super Man of Our Industrial Age |author=Ralph Bergstresser |page=15 |publisher=Health Research Books |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-7873-0094-4}}</ref>
The book covers, among other topics, the story of Tesla's father's inspiration for his career in engineering, shows his theories of electricity that went against the scientific establishment, explores the friendships of Tesla, investigates the story of Tesla's lost [[Nobel Prize]], and explains Tesla's investigations of the paranormal.<ref name=nytreview>{{cite news|last=Kaempffert|first=Waldemar|authorlink=Waldemar Kaempffert|title=Electric Sorcerer|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1945/02/04/94852087.html|accessdate=28 October 2015|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 February 1945}}</ref>
